5 Light, clean broth. Superior decor. Good people.  I took two coworkers to check out this new addition to the Las Vegas restaurant scene recently.  Here's the cast of characters:  "Tex" - Married, born in Vietnam, grew up in Texas. His dialect takes some getting used to. "NY" - Single, from "Lung Guy Land", moved to NevODDuh and graduated with an advanced degree from UNLV. and...Me.  Tex prefers a more flavorful broth, what I term a "dirty" broth. I prefer a lighter, cleaner broth. NY kept raving about the basketball-sized fish in the aquarium.  NY ordered Pho with chicken (what the beautiful lady serving the food said was "white boy pho", which we all laughed about). I had rare steak with mine. Tex had something I cannot pronounce. :)   The decor was acknowledged by all of us as superior. I prefer the broth here, in comparison with Tex.  I think once this place is "discovered" (between Twain and Desert Inn on Jones) there won't be an empty seat in the house.   I discovered from the other half of this dynamic duo team running this restaurant (the guy with the apron slaving over boiling beef bones and water) that this wonderful couple is from Los Angeles from the famed Pho 87 known to all who appreciate good noodles, luscious broth, and the freshest leafy and snappy ingredients as accouterment. You get all that, and good karma as a bonus when you eat here!   Fantastic experience for all of us. You will not be disappointed!  Worth a $30 cab ride? You bet! If you are driving, head west on Desert Inn and turn left (south) on Jones. Just past the Bank of America on your left hand side is this gorgeous excursion into flavor! If you hit Twain, turn around and go back. You won't be sorry.  Very extensive, authentic menu, according to Tex.
1 Ok, Let me first start off by saying the woman "owner" is extremely nice and the customer service was great!   With that being said the food was terrible. I was trying to find a reason to like the food just because the lady was so nice. My GF was a little sketchy to go here due to the fact that it was 1:30 in the afternoon and there were no cars in the parking lot, So it was a relief to see a table inside eating. We ordered PHO GA which is chicken PHO. It took a while to get our food so the anticipation was great! Finally it arrived......... Broth was very clear with some brown pieces floating around in it. When we asked what it was she stated "brown onion". The brown onion completely over powerd the soup and was terrible. Next, there was white chunks floating around, after further review we determined it was some sort of meat. This had no resemblance to chicken, not similar texture , smell, taste, nothing to make me think this was chicken. After a minute I thought what the hell I am going to try it, It tasted like a grainy, gamey taste, not horrible but def not chicken. I added a ton of hot sauce to give it some flavor but no luck.  Here's the deal, I am not speaking for all the food but the PHO is horrible if you want some great PHO go to PHO SO #1.
5 Quite a few few pho restaurants have opened up in Las Vegas over the years.  This one is by far the best.  It all comes down to the soup and this place has great soup.  Their large bowl, which is HUGE, is still under $8.  I haven't tried any of the other dishes, but my friend had their pork chop recently and we both agreed taht the portion was much bigger than any other place.  The restaurant is owner operated and the owners are very friendly.  The atmoshpere is no frills, but the food is great.  I won't go to another pho place.
4 We found this place through yelp, because of an in depth review by another yelper. We were greeted by two people who were both funny and interesting. The restaurant was kept very well, clean and pleasant atmosphere, although not in a Vietnamese atmosphere, this place was a Japanese restaurant and Chinese restaurant before it was this. But its nice regardless. And I am sure hoping they got a good deal on the space. We ordered the shrimp cold summer type rolls, grilled pork pho and lean chicken pho and a coconut drink and preserved lemon drink. The summer roll was fresh and delicious. The phos were fantastic! The grilled pork pho was extraordinary, the broth and ingredients were fresh and tasty. The "white boy" pho, the chicken, was light and perfect.  The coconut was a real one not some outta the can, and the preserved lemon drink was authentic and good. They have a contest pho that is gigantic...if you can eat it in 15 minutes its free! We will definitely be going back! LOVED this place! Thanks Yelp for getting us there.  The chef/owner(Charlie) is funny, entertaining, and cooked at pho87 in Los Angeles under his mother for 22 years before opening this place here. His experience and care with the ingredients really shows.
