5 Man this pho is so good its just like I "popped a molly I'm sweatin', WHOOO!"  "Don't blee me juh watch" (Trinidad James voice).  I enjoy turning on those not knowin...I got a grip of heads on the pho train and I ain't stoppin' now.  Suprisingly, as much as I love pho, I can't have it too often.  I try not to overkill it and become desensitized to its dopeness.  This way, each time I come through, its well worth it.  Moreover, this pho spot is a bit secluded when it comes to Chinatown Vietnamese cuisine restaurants nearby or on Spring Mountain Road.  You can find it in the cuts just south of Spring Mountain going down Jones.  There is a shady European eatery across the street, which I have a conspiracy theory that its a front for some illegal activity.  Seems like all these goons drop by and suspiciously look around before entering and leaving with a garbage bag that goes in the trunk or other mean looking henchmen in cheap leather coats and toothpicks.  They remind me of the guys in the movie, Taken.  Oops getting off track here...  Ok back to the matter at hand, perfection is perfected so I let em understand...  I have had my share of pho in my day, and I must say that this is by far the best spot in LV.  I know I know, everyone may arguably have other spots in mind, Pho Saigon 8, Pho So 1, and so forth.  But no one can beat the experience you get when you eat here for several reasons.  1)  The owner and lone waitress, who reminds me of a good friend, is hilarious.  She is so anal and particular about things, its not even funny.  Its like she got OCD but in denial.  She is quick to put in her 2 cents and has no filter for her opinion, I respect that.  My boy doesn't use chopsticks and was using a fork to eat his pho and a single chopstick to help break off the ever so tender oxtail meat from the bone.  I sweat ol' girl looked like she was gonna bust out some crouching tiger...she give him the death stare for an akward period before shaking her head and leaving.  All her actions are funny and if you take things too seriously or personally, this may not be the place for you.  Otherwise, chat with her and you will see she is a character.  2)   The broth is unrivaled!  No broth even comes close...none of that can style pre maid broth or MSG loaded renditions that leave you parched and crawling out the door looking like the dude that dies in a C grade horror flick when the life gets sucked out of you.  The broth is clear and fresh.  Granted that every pho spot has good and bad days, my first test is a few teaspoons of straight up broth before I start demolishing everything else  3)  The place is in shambles.  Almost like something out of hoarders intervention.  It looks like it was formerly an Asian buffet of some sort that was transformed.  I don't ever find the place crowded and usually get seated near the window like always.  Seems like only 25% of the dining area is used.  The bathroom, forget about it....but hey it gets the job done.  All of these factors may seem like it can have a negative bearing on the experience here, yet, personally it makes me appreciate the place even more.  I came here for pho, not to look at wall hangings or other fengshui or Asian decor.  They get down to business and the pho comes out quick.  So if you are one of those that want a balanced foodie experience with the ambiance of a clean place with good service and food, go elsewhere.  However, you will still miss out on the best pho in town.  I only go with two different main dishes here...the oxtail pho or the dac biet.  I tend to get a little bit of their home made sate sauce for a garlic oily flavor additive, but a little dab will do ya.  Some appetizers on the side accent the meal well too.  Be careful about the size portions as well.  The price on the menu may not reflect the price for larger sizes and the medium is a hefty portion in itself, trust me.  Now if you really wanna test your limits, take the PhoZilla challenge!  Here is more info on that: http://pho87.net/
3 This place is moderate, but there are better places to eat pho and oxtail soup.  The waitress, or owner, was nice and made a few jokes. She checked up on us often, but, like other reviewers said, there was barely any business going on. She was friendly and didn't radiate a bad atmosphere. She had an ego about the restaurant's food, but it could have been better.  The prices are not worth the amount of food you receive. I ordered rice noodle with the oxtail for $10. The food was good, but they gave you a small bowl for the price you paid. The noodles were thick, the broth was good, and the oxtail was soft and tasty. There are many pho places that charge $7 for a large bowl, but Pho 87's $10 bowl would be considered a small order in those other pho restaurants.  I wouldn't recommend Pho 87 to other people, but it's not horrible as other reviewers have said.
